0.05) for infrastructure and pipeline steps.\n\nPublishing safe content depends primarily on the system's ability to persist and queue the post correctly—0.8 Integration. The logic itself is straightforward (0.1 Unit), with minor allocations to System (0.05) and Workflow (0.05) for infrastructure and downstream steps.\n\nLatency across a 5-second threshold can't be measured without real models and infrastructure running end-to-end. Workflow carries the heaviest weight (0.4) since the full pipeline with actual model inference determines whether the threshold is met. Agentic (0.3) accounts for model inference time, System (0.2) for network calls, and Integration (0.1) for potential bottlenecks in the pipeline.\n\nWhen the vision model becomes unavailable, the system should queue posts for retry instead of auto-approving them. This is primarily an error-handling and queue management problem—0.7 Integration. The exception logic itself is simple (0.1 Unit), with System (0.15) for queue infrastructure and Workflow (0.05) for the overall retry flow.\n\nFor borderline images, the model must return consistent classifications for identical inputs. This hinges on model behavior—0.7 Agentic. Caching mechanisms (0.2 Integration) and infrastructure consistency (0.05 System) support this, with minimal Unit testing (0.05) needed for cache key logic.\n\nReconsidering unavailability: the behavior depends on how the system reacts when the model is actually unreachable. A real failure involves network partitions or service downtime (System level), but mocking an exception at Integration level catches bugs in the retry queue logic itself. The minimum to detect the failure is Integration, though System testing would catch infrastructure-related issues that mocks might hide.\n\nThe core question is whether a mock can expose the actual failure. If I mock the model to throw a TimeoutError, I can verify the system queues the post rather than auto-approving it. This catches the bug in exception handling logic. So behavior 5 is Integration level.\n\nThe real failure stems from a code bug: when the model raises an exception, the system incorrectly auto-approves instead of queuing. Mocking the exception and checking queue behavior directly tests this logic.\n\nHowever, there's a deeper consideration. The actual unavailability might manifest differently than expected—the real model could return null, timeout in a different way, or behave unexpectedly when the service is down. Catching these edge cases requires testing against an actual unavailable service, which is System level. To catch all possible failures including how the real model actually behaves when unavailable, I need System testing. But the minimum to catch the core logic bug is Integration.\n\nFor behavior 5, I'm settling on Integration as the baseline (0.7 probability) since it validates the queueing logic when unavailability is mocked, with System (0.2) being more thorough for real-world scenarios. Now I should double-check my reasoning on the earlier behaviors to ensure consistency across all five.\n\nLooking back at the level definitions, System covers real HTTP calls and external APIs, while Agentic specifically targets model intelligence and non-determinism. This distinction matters—testing whether an API responds is different from testing whether a model's output is correct. If I'm verifying API behavior or latency, that's System; if I'm validating the model's reasoning or accuracy, that's Agentic.\n\nFor the explicit content detection behavior, I need to confirm the model actually catches inappropriate material—that's testing model correctness, so Agentic. The latency SLA is trickier since it spans the full pipeline with multiple steps, making it Workflow. But the key insight from the task is focusing on what would catch a *real failure*, not just happy-path verification. That means I should consider what infrastructure would actually surface a problem—whether that's model inference slowness, network delays, or the orchestration breaking down across steps.\n\nFor explicit content, a real failure would be the system flagging inappropriate material as safe and publishing it. To catch that, I need an actual image with explicit content and the real vision model classifying it—mocking the model wouldn't test the actual failure mode. Same logic applies to the consistency behavior: submitting the same borderline image twice to the real model would surface if decisions vary unexpectedly. Both require the actual model, confirming they're Agentic tests.\n\nNow for the test descriptions themselves. Behavior 1 should verify that explicit images get flagged and held, using a real test image known to contain inappropriate material. Behavior 2 checks if obfuscated hate speech—with letter substitution or unicode lookalikes—gets caught by the text model and held. Behavior 3 is different: it mocks both models to return 'safe' and confirms the post publishes successfully. Behavior 4 measures whether the entire pipeline from image preprocessing through the publish decision completes within 5 seconds.\n\nBehavior 5 tests the retry mechanism when the vision model times out or fails—the post should queue for retry rather than auto-approve. Behavior 6 ensures consistency by submitting the same borderline image multiple times within a short window and verifying each gets the same decision.\n\nFor the plan_consistent analysis, Behavior 1 is agentic because it needs the real vision model to classify an actual explicit image. The test submits a real explicit image and verifies it's flagged.\n\nBehavior 2 is also agentic since understanding obfuscated hate speech requires the real text model's semantic capabilities. Behavior 3 can work at integration level by mocking the models to return safe results and verifying the post publishes, though integration testing better ensures database and queue persistence. Behavior 4 requires workflow-level testing with real models to measure