 distinguish between what's being tested. The consistency of moderation decisions on the same image could stem from either the model's inherent consistency (Agentic) or a caching mechanism (Integration). The test is checking whether repeated submissions yield identical results within a short timeframe.\n\nSince the behavior describes the system's moderation decision rather than just the model's raw output, and assuming the system implements caching to optimize performance, testing at the Integration level makes more sense—I'd mock the model and verify the caching mechanism works correctly. This captures the actual failure mode: whether the system reliably returns consistent decisions through its caching layer.\n\nHowever, the behavior description doesn't explicitly state caching is used, so testing at the Agentic level with real model calls would be more robust and catch consistency issues regardless of implementation details. The phrase \"within a short window\" does suggest a time-based caching strategy, which points back toward Integration testing. I'll prioritize Agentic testing to ensure the behavior holds even without caching, while recognizing that Integration testing would validate the specific optimization mechanism. Workflow: 0.05\n\nSum = 1.0\n\nActually, reconsidering the behavior description: \"The moderation decision for a borderline image is consistent when the same image is submitted multiple times within a short window.\"\n\nThe core distinction is whether this tests caching implementation or model determinism. If it's checking that cached results are returned, that's an Integration test—submit the image, verify the cache stores it, then resubmit and confirm the cached decision is used. If it's verifying the model itself produces identical outputs on repeated submissions, that's an Agentic test focused on model consistency. The \"short window\" phrasing leans toward the caching interpretation, suggesting the system should recognize and reuse the decision rather than recompute it.\n\nGiven that caching is a reasonable design choice for handling borderline cases, I'll weight this as primarily Integration with Agentic as a secondary consideration. The real failure would be inconsistent results on resubmission—either a cache miss when one should exist or the model producing different outputs. My revised probabilities: Unit 0.05, Integration 0.5, System 0.05, Agentic 0.35, Workflow 0.05.\n\nThe key distinction is whether the inconsistency stems from model non-determinism (requiring Agentic testing) or cache implementation bugs (requiring Integration testing). Since the behavior mentions \"within a short window,\" that phrasing suggests caching is part of the design, making cache failures more probable than raw model variance. However, I should account for both possibilities—Integration catches cache bugs while Agentic catches model inconsistency.\n\nModel consistency feels more foundational though. If the underlying model produces different outputs for identical inputs, caching won't solve that. So Agentic testing takes priority. I'm settling on Agentic as the minimum level needed, with probabilities weighted heavily toward Agentic (0.7) and some allocation to Integration (0.2) for the caching scenario.\n\nMy final answers are: Agentic, Agentic, Integration, Workflow, Integration, Agentic. Now I'll format these as JSON.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13402,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13402},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c28a5431-5612-49e7-a154-33be4685b2bb","uuid":"4e354a9d-9690-4774-9aad-c4a3a9f12abf"}
